did.abstract: This collection contains correspondence, articles, lecture notes, essays, biographical data, and subject and research files. These materials represent the personal papers of Marcus Raskin, the materials he created and collected with the Institute for Policy Studies and as a professor at The George Washington University. The materials date from 1949-2013.

arrangement.p: Organized into 9 series: Biographical data; Writings (by Marcus Raskin and collected by him); Lectures, conferences, and seminars; Institute for Policy Studies; PATHS; Correspondence; People; Subject and research files, and The Liberal Project.

bioghist.head: Biographical note
bioghist.p: Marcus Raskin (b. 1934-2017 ) is the co-founder of the progressive think tank, the Institute for Policy Studies, located in Washington, DC and an author of numerous books and articles. In 1961 Harvard sociologist David Riesman recommended Raskin, a recent graduate of the University of Chicago Law School, to McGeorge Bundy, the National Security Advisor to the newly elected president, John F. Kennedy. Raskin served as Bundy's assistant on national security affairs and disarmament as a member of the Special Staff of the National Security Council. In 1963, Raskin left government service and founded, with fellow government worker Richard Barnet, the Institute for Policy Studies (IPS). Much of Raskin's initial work with IPS focused on opposing the Vietnam War. He co-authored The Viet-nam Reader with Bernard Fall in 1965, which was used in dozens of teach-ins across the country.

Marcus Raskin is the author and co-author of more than twenty books and countless articles related to the progressive movement including topics such as as anti-war, liberalism, anti-nuclear movement, and pro-environment.
He is also a professor of public policy at The George Washington University's School of Public Policy and Public Administration.

bioghist.head: Historical note
bioghist.p: The Institute for Policy Studies, a left-leaning think tank, was founded in 1963 by Marcus Raskin and Richard Barnet. The two were Kennedy administration staff members who formed the IPS in an attempt to persaude government policy-makers to embrace progressive ideas. By 1965, IPS, was fully involved in the anti-Vietnam War movement. Raskin and Bernard Fall, an IPS fellow, edited The Viet-Nam Reader which became an essential text for the teach-in movement that was sweeping across college campuses.Over the years, the IPS has become a place to generate and test progressive ideas. Some ideas such as the Model Cities program and Teachers Corps became policy. Throughout its life-time, IPS scholars have written books, produced films, and lead social movements all with the goal of educating and influencing key policymakers and the general public. Areas of focus have been peace, justice, and the environment. The principles articulated by Raskin and Barnet for IPS included: not taking government funding to ensure impartiality, public scholarship, building alternatives, and social inventions.

bioghist.head: Historical note
bioghist.p: Marcus Raskin serves as the director of the Institute for Policy Studies' Paths for the 21st Century Project. The Paths for Reconstruction in the 21st Century project links knowledge to the betterment of the human condition through thinking and practical action. The project is based on the assumption that a renaissance of moral action and thought is on the immediate horizon. The PATHS project has produced a multi-volume book that explores international organizations and politics in order to create new models for fostering equality and alternatives for the 21st century on questions of peace, economic and social justice, cultural rights, democratic reconstruction, and racial and gender equality.

arrangement.head: Arrangement
arrangement.p: This series contains three subseries: People, correspondence, research and writings, and the Liberal Project.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: This series includes items that were donated in 2014 and spans from 1952-2013, with the bulk of the material coming from 1959-1962. It includes correspondence, memos, press releases, essays, and articles related to the Liberal Project, of which Marcus Raskin was the secretary. The Liberal Project started in the late 1950s-early 1960s and was comprised of scholars, scientists and experts, and political leaders who sought to redefine the term liberalism and better apply it to current events. Topics addressed within the project included International Relations, Law and the Judiciary, Education, Science and Culture, Economic and Industrial Affairs, and Defense Policy. The Liberal Project also published many of their essays in a 1962 book, "The Liberal Papers." This series includes files on the various members of the Liberal Project as well. These files consist of correspondence and essays written by the members.

Finally, this series contains general correspondence, works written and collected by Marcus Raskin on the topics listed above for the Liberal Project, and articles and programs for various lectures and conferences he attended. It also includes organized files with outlines of Raskin's correspondence and memos in the Wisconsin History folders. This series contains materials associated with the Liberal Project between 1952 and 2013.
